    <h1>Wild Animals</h1>

    <h2>Bear</h2>
    <p>The bear is a large, furry mammal that lives in forests, <br />
        mountains, and tundras. They are solitary animals, except <br />
        during mating season or when food is abundant.</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Weight: 300 to 700 kg</li>
        <li>Length: Up to 3 meters</li>
        <li>Main food sources: Fish, fruits, honey, small mammals</li>
        <li>Life expectancy: 20 to 30 years</li>
    </ul>
    <img src="https://plus.unsplash.com/premium_photo-1661849977833-c18cd1c7e295?w=500&auto=format&fit=crop&q=60&ixlib=rb-4.1.0&ixid=M3wxMjA3fDB8MHxzZWFyY2h8MXx8YmVhcnxlbnwwfHwwfHx8MA%3D%3D" width="300" alt="Bear">


    <h2>Lion</h2>
    <p>The lion is known as the king of the jungle. It lives in prides <br />
        and is mostly found in Africa. Lions are strong and agile <br />
        carnivores, with males having a distinctive mane.</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Weight: 150 to 250 kg</li>
        <li>Length: Up to 2.5 meters, not including the tail</li>
        <li>Main food sources: Antelopes, zebras, buffaloes</li>
        <li>Life expectancy: 10 to 14 years in the wild</li>
    </ul>
    <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/73/Lion_waiting_in_Namibia.jpg" width="300">

    <h2>Shark</h2>
    <p>The shark is a cartilaginous fish that lives in the oceans. <br />
        There are many species, but in general, they are fast <br />
        and efficient marine predators.</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Weight: Varies by species; the great white shark can weigh up to 1,100 kg</li>
        <li>Length: From 1 to 6 meters (or more for larger species)</li>
        <li>Main food sources: Fish, seals, squids</li>
        <li>Life expectancy: 20 to 70 years depending on the species</li>
    </ul>
    <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/56/White_shark.jpg" width="300">
</body>
